1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:07,000
I'm here today to talk about thinking for yourself.

2
00:00:07,000 --> 00:00:12,000
And I must admit I did use AI to help me think about it.

3
00:00:12,000 --> 00:00:15,000
The AI is not lost on me.

4
00:00:15,000 --> 00:00:19,000
But the way I did so is not by using AI as an assistant

5
00:00:19,000 --> 00:00:21,000
to help me prepare this talk faster.

6
00:00:21,000 --> 00:00:25,000
Rather, I use AI as a tool for thought.

7
00:00:25,000 --> 00:00:29,000
And by the end of this talk, I will have explained what I mean by that

8
00:00:29,000 --> 00:00:34,000
why it's important and give you a glimpse of how it might work.

9
00:00:34,000 --> 00:00:36,000
But first I need to set the scene.

10
00:00:36,000 --> 00:00:40,000
Let's look at a day in the life of a 21st century knowledge worker.

11
00:00:40,000 --> 00:00:45,000
I arrive at my office and look at my inbox full of emails.

12
00:00:45,000 --> 00:00:49,000
Let's summarize it.

13
00:00:49,000 --> 00:00:53,000
I'm struggling to figure out how to respond here.

14
00:00:53,000 --> 00:00:56,000
So let's get AI to write a response.

15
00:00:56,000 --> 00:01:01,000
Next, I need to write a report from struck by the blank page problem.

16
00:01:01,000 --> 00:01:05,000
I know I'll drop in some resources and get an AI draft.

17
00:01:05,000 --> 00:01:07,000
Looks good to me.

18
00:01:07,000 --> 00:01:10,000
By the way, the writer's block used to be staring at a blank page.

19
00:01:10,000 --> 00:01:13,000
Now it's staring at a page that AI filled out for me

20
00:01:13,000 --> 00:01:15,000
and wondering if I agree with it.

21
00:01:15,000 --> 00:01:19,000
I've become a professional validator of a robot's opinions.

22
00:01:19,000 --> 00:01:23,000
I've got some data to analyze.

23
00:01:23,000 --> 00:01:27,000
Maybe AI can analyze this data for me?

24
00:01:27,000 --> 00:01:29,000
Probably correct.

25
00:01:29,000 --> 00:01:32,000
Okay, I've got to make a deck as well.

26
00:01:32,000 --> 00:01:34,000
You know the drill.

27
00:01:34,000 --> 00:01:38,000
All right, I was supposed to prototype something as well.

28
00:01:38,000 --> 00:01:40,000
Okay, let me vibe code something.

29
00:01:40,000 --> 00:01:42,000
All right, all this looks good.

30
00:01:42,000 --> 00:01:44,000
Let's go.

31
00:01:44,000 --> 00:01:47,000
This isn't a vision of the future.

32
00:01:47,000 --> 00:01:51,000
This is a completely plausible, if slightly exaggerated picture of the world

33
00:01:51,000 --> 00:01:54,000
of knowledge work today.

34
00:01:54,000 --> 00:01:57,000
Welcome to the age of outsourced reason

35
00:01:57,000 --> 00:02:01,000
where the knowledge worker no longer engages with the materials of their craft.

36
00:02:01,000 --> 00:02:03,000
We've become intellectual tourists.

37
00:02:03,000 --> 00:02:06,000
In our own work, we visit ideas.

38
00:02:06,000 --> 00:02:09,000
We don't inhabit them.

39
00:02:09,000 --> 00:02:16,000
Our relationship to our work is entirely intermediated by AI.

40
00:02:16,000 --> 00:02:18,000
Some might say alienated.

41
00:02:18,000 --> 00:02:20,000
We've heard that story before.

42
00:02:20,000 --> 00:02:23,000
What's wrong with this picture?

43
00:02:23,000 --> 00:02:27,000
For one thing, it's only one step removed from this, which is important.

44
00:02:27,000 --> 00:02:29,000
But that's a different talk.

45
00:02:29,000 --> 00:02:39,000
What I want to focus on today is that using AI in this way can have profound implications on human thought.

46
00:02:39,000 --> 00:02:41,000
Consider creativity.

47
00:02:41,000 --> 00:02:44,000
On an individual level, we might think that AI is a creativity boost,

48
00:02:44,000 --> 00:02:47,000
giving us rapid access to new ideas.

49
00:02:47,000 --> 00:02:51,000
But numerous studies have shown that on a collective level,

50
00:02:51,000 --> 00:02:58,000
knowledge workers using AI assistance produce a smaller range of ideas than a group working manually.

51
00:02:58,000 --> 00:03:01,000
We've created a hive mind,

52
00:03:01,000 --> 00:03:06,000
so the hive is really boring and keeps suggesting the same five ideas.

53
00:03:06,000 --> 00:03:08,000
Consider critical thinking.

54
00:03:08,000 --> 00:03:12,000
We surveyed knowledge workers about their use of AI.

55
00:03:12,000 --> 00:03:15,000
They reported that they put less effort into critical thinking,

56
00:03:15,000 --> 00:03:20,000
when working with AI, then when working manually.

57
00:03:20,000 --> 00:03:27,000
And this fact was greater when they had greater confidence in AI and less confidence in themselves.

58
00:03:27,000 --> 00:03:30,000
Consider memory.

59
00:03:30,000 --> 00:03:35,000
When people rely on AI to write for them, they remember less of what they wrote.

60
00:03:35,000 --> 00:03:42,000
And when they read AI-generated summaries, it's hardly surprising that they remember less than if they'd read the document.

61
00:03:42,000 --> 00:03:48,000
And finally, consider a meta-cognition, which is the ability to think about your own thinking process.

62
00:03:48,000 --> 00:03:55,000
Working with AI requires significant meta-cognitive reasoning about your task goals, decomposing the task,

63
00:03:55,000 --> 00:03:59,000
the applicability of Gen AI, your ability to evaluate the output.

64
00:03:59,000 --> 00:04:04,000
These are things which are built into the process of working directly with a material,

65
00:04:04,000 --> 00:04:09,000
and which become problematic when that material engagement becomes intermediated.

66
00:04:09,000 --> 00:04:13,000
Basically, we've become middle managers for our own thoughts.

67
00:04:13,000 --> 00:04:15,000
So what's the score?

68
00:04:15,000 --> 00:04:17,000
We have fewer ideas.

69
00:04:17,000 --> 00:04:19,000
We think about them less critically.

70
00:04:19,000 --> 00:04:24,000
We remember them less well, and we have a harder time doing it.

71
00:04:24,000 --> 00:04:30,000
Taken together, we can see that AI assisted workflows can have profound effects on human thinking.

72
00:04:30,000 --> 00:04:34,000
And this extends even to seemingly trivial mundane tasks,

73
00:04:34,000 --> 00:04:40,000
because these everyday opportunities for exercising our creativity, our critical thinking, and our memory are essential

74
00:04:40,000 --> 00:04:48,000
for protecting our cognitive musculature, and allow us to rise to the occasion when an exceptionally complex task comes our way.

75
00:04:48,000 --> 00:04:54,000
Studies show that when we don't use our brains, they get worse at brain things.

76
00:04:54,000 --> 00:04:59,000
Nobel Prize Committee, please hold your applause.

77
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:04,000
Is this the cost of progress?

78
00:05:04,000 --> 00:05:07,000
We solved the problem of having to think.

79
00:05:07,000 --> 00:05:11,000
Unfortunately, thinking wasn't actually a problem.

80
00:05:11,000 --> 00:05:18,000
It's like we invented a cure for exercise, and then wondered why we're out of breath all the time.

81
00:05:18,000 --> 00:05:24,000
Doesn't have to be this way.

82
00:05:25,000 --> 00:05:30,000
Beyond AI as an assistant, I believe that AI should be a tool for thought.

83
00:05:30,000 --> 00:05:33,000
AI should challenge, not obey.

84
00:05:33,000 --> 00:05:40,000
And I believe that right at this moment we are at a critical juncture, where the world if work is poised to be transformed by generative AI,

85
00:05:40,000 --> 00:05:46,000
and we must act now to shape and drive that transformation towards humanistic values.

86
00:05:46,000 --> 00:05:51,000
Of these two diverging roads, we must take the one less traveled.

87
00:05:51,000 --> 00:05:56,000
The job done, a tool for thought helps us better understand the job.

88
00:05:56,000 --> 00:06:01,000
Beyond getting it done faster, it helps us get it done better.

89
00:06:01,000 --> 00:06:07,000
Beyond getting us to the right answers, a tool for thought helps us ask the right questions.

90
00:06:07,000 --> 00:06:12,000
Beyond automating known processes, it helps us explore the unknown.

91
00:06:12,000 --> 00:06:14,000
What does this look like?

92
00:06:14,000 --> 00:06:22,000
What I'm about to show you is a prototype developed by my colleagues and me at the tools for thought team at Microsoft Research in Cambridge.

93
00:06:22,000 --> 00:06:26,000
Now, please bear in mind that this is a live research prototype.

94
00:06:26,000 --> 00:06:28,000
It's not a product.

95
00:06:28,000 --> 00:06:35,000
And it's just one of a series of explorations that our team is conducting to study how different modes of working with AI can enhance human thought.

96
00:06:35,000 --> 00:06:39,000
So let's look at a fictitious example.

97
00:06:40,000 --> 00:06:46,000
Clara and her colleagues run a company that sells bottled beverages.

98
00:06:46,000 --> 00:06:55,000
They've just had a meeting to discuss a new industry report that seems to have some pretty important findings about consumer preferences for sustainable packaging.

99
00:06:55,000 --> 00:07:01,000
Clara's colleagues have asked her to write a proposal arguing for how the company ought to respond.

100
00:07:01,000 --> 00:07:04,000
So she really needs to get the grips with this proposal.

101
00:07:04,000 --> 00:07:07,000
She really needs to get the grips with this report.

102
00:07:07,000 --> 00:07:13,000
Understand its findings and its data and how it fits into her business context.

103
00:07:13,000 --> 00:07:19,000
She starts by loading some documents into her workspace.

104
00:07:19,000 --> 00:07:22,000
There's the meeting transcript to remind her what was discussed.

105
00:07:22,000 --> 00:07:25,000
There's a recent internal report from her own business.

106
00:07:25,000 --> 00:07:29,000
And of course, there's the industry report which she opens.

107
00:07:30,000 --> 00:07:34,000
She sees an overview of the document along with section by section summaries.

108
00:07:34,000 --> 00:07:36,000
Except these aren't really just summaries.

109
00:07:36,000 --> 00:07:38,000
We think of them more as lenses.

110
00:07:38,000 --> 00:07:45,000
They're customizable micro representations of the text that can emphasize what is most relevant to the task at hand.

111
00:07:45,000 --> 00:07:49,000
So in this case, Clara selects the consumer's lens.

112
00:07:51,000 --> 00:07:53,000
She can select a section for deeper reading.

113
00:07:53,000 --> 00:07:55,000
In this case, the first one.

114
00:07:56,000 --> 00:08:04,000
As she reads, she makes notes about her thoughts and highlights excerpts from the document.

115
00:08:04,000 --> 00:08:10,000
As she reads, she also sees AI-generated commentary and critiques.

116
00:08:10,000 --> 00:08:13,000
We call these provocations.

117
00:08:13,000 --> 00:08:19,000
Here's a provocation that raises a potential opportunity which she highlights and annotates.

118
00:08:20,000 --> 00:08:27,000
Note how this process is a hybrid of completely manual reading and completely relying on AI to read for you.

119
00:08:27,000 --> 00:08:32,000
Clara still reads, but intentionally and strategically.

120
00:08:32,000 --> 00:08:39,000
Now, as Clara is working, she's building up an outline of her argument manually in this pane on the right.

121
00:08:39,000 --> 00:08:46,000
This outline is lightly structured and allows her to sketch out the flow of her argument at a high level,

122
00:08:46,000 --> 00:08:50,000
while still retaining deep connections and being grounded in the source documents,

123
00:08:50,000 --> 00:08:54,000
as a result of which we can already generate a draft of the proposal.

124
00:08:54,000 --> 00:08:59,000
And Clara can do things here like add a heading to the outline to generate a paragraph.

125
00:08:59,000 --> 00:09:05,000
But what I want to draw your attention to here is that while this text is AI-generated,

126
00:09:05,000 --> 00:09:10,000
Clara has a completely different relationship to this text than if she just dropped in some documents and said,

127
00:09:10,000 --> 00:09:16,000
write me a report, because this text is deeply rooted in a cognitively effortful,

128
00:09:16,000 --> 00:09:20,000
but interactionally effortless thought process.

129
00:09:20,000 --> 00:09:30,000
It reflects Clara's decisions, Clara's judgments, Clara's unique personal professional expertise.

130
00:09:30,000 --> 00:09:35,000
She sees another provocation this time in the outline.

131
00:09:35,000 --> 00:09:41,000
In this case, she decides that while the provocation is useful, she does not need to address it.

132
00:09:41,000 --> 00:09:46,000
Unlike typical AI suggestions, provocations are not meant to be applicable all the time.

133
00:09:46,000 --> 00:09:49,000
They're instead meant to stimulate your thinking about your work,

134
00:09:49,000 --> 00:09:55,000
because if you understand your work well enough, deeply enough to make the confident decision,

135
00:09:55,000 --> 00:10:02,000
not to accept a piece of feedback, then the feedback process is still working as intended.

136
00:10:02,000 --> 00:10:09,000
But we're not done yet. Clara has entirely new ways of interacting with this text because of generative AI.

137
00:10:09,000 --> 00:10:14,000
A really simple example is that she can just resize a paragraph to change its length.

138
00:10:14,000 --> 00:10:18,000
She can also rapidly test different versions of this text.

139
00:10:18,000 --> 00:10:25,000
For instance, in this paragraph, she's wondering whether it would be more effective if it took a more inspirational or more practical tone.

140
00:10:25,000 --> 00:10:30,000
She selects one of these customizable dimensions,

141
00:10:30,000 --> 00:10:35,000
and previews a few alternatives, and selects one.

142
00:10:35,000 --> 00:10:40,000
And at select strategic points, indeed, she writes.

143
00:10:40,000 --> 00:10:49,000
As she writes, she sees provocations that, rather than auto-completing her ideas, they raise alternatives.

144
00:10:49,000 --> 00:10:56,000
They identify fallacies, they offer counter-arguments to help her string and then develop her own argument.

145
00:10:56,000 --> 00:11:00,000
There's something you won't find anywhere in this interface.

146
00:11:00,000 --> 00:11:01,000
That's a chat box.

147
00:11:01,000 --> 00:11:10,000
Clara's not having to chat with anything to do her work, yet she is silently and appropriately assisted by her computer as a computer,

148
00:11:10,000 --> 00:11:12,000
and not as an ersatz human.

149
00:11:12,000 --> 00:11:21,000
To put it simply, we have gone from this to this.

150
00:11:21,000 --> 00:11:28,000
Throughout this process, Clara has been assisted, and yes, probably worked faster because of AI.

151
00:11:28,000 --> 00:11:32,000
But she's also maintained direct material engagement at strategic points.

152
00:11:32,000 --> 00:11:38,000
She read the relevant portions of the document herself. She constructed her decisions on her argument herself.

153
00:11:38,000 --> 00:11:41,000
And ultimately, it can be said she has written this document herself.

154
00:11:41,000 --> 00:11:44,000
Moreover, she worked better because of AI.

155
00:11:44,000 --> 00:11:55,000
AI provocations at every stage of the process kept her metacognitively engaged, always looking for critiques, alternatives, and lateral moves.

156
00:11:55,000 --> 00:12:01,000
We have been studying the effects of tools like this, and the results are promising.

157
00:12:01,000 --> 00:12:06,000
You can demonstrably reintroduce critical thinking into AI-assisted workflow.

158
00:12:06,000 --> 00:12:11,000
You can reverse the loss of creativity and enhance it instead.

159
00:12:11,000 --> 00:12:20,000
You can build powerful tools for memory that enable knowledge workers to read and write at speed with greater intentionality and remember it too.

160
00:12:20,000 --> 00:12:27,000
It turns out, with the right principles of design, you can build tools that are the best of both worlds,

161
00:12:27,000 --> 00:12:33,000
applying the awesome speed and flexibility of this technology to protect and enhance human thought.

162
00:12:33,000 --> 00:12:41,000
These are simple, general principles, like ensuring that the tool preserves material engagement,

163
00:12:41,000 --> 00:12:45,000
offers productive resistance and scaffolds metacognition.

164
00:12:45,000 --> 00:12:53,000
And while we've been primarily studying professional knowledge workers, we believe that these principles can extend to all aspects of AI use,

165
00:12:53,000 --> 00:12:59,000
including when we use it in our daily lives, our hobbies, and even in education.

166
00:12:59,000 --> 00:13:03,000
I repeat, efficiency is not the aim of tools for thought.

167
00:13:03,000 --> 00:13:08,000
Better thinking is, but sometimes you can't have both.

168
00:13:08,000 --> 00:13:12,000
I used to think there was no such thing as a free lunch in human thinking.

169
00:13:12,000 --> 00:13:17,000
This is so much better than a free lunch. This is a lunch that pays you to eat it.

170
00:13:17,000 --> 00:13:25,000
I want to close with some thoughts on the values that we have in developing AI software.

171
00:13:25,000 --> 00:13:30,000
What if AI gets to the point where it can do a better job of thinking than humans?

172
00:13:30,000 --> 00:13:35,000
Why should we care so much about protecting and augmenting human thought?

173
00:13:35,000 --> 00:13:41,000
There's two reasons. First, there may always be ways of thinking that remain unique human strengths,

174
00:13:41,000 --> 00:13:44,000
of which we may not even be aware.

175
00:13:44,000 --> 00:13:54,000
Second, perhaps more importantly, we take the position that the ability to think well is essential for human agency and empowerment and flourishing.

176
00:13:54,000 --> 00:13:57,000
This echoes an ancient question.

177
00:13:57,000 --> 00:14:05,000
People once asked, you know, if writing, if books, if the internet can remember for us, does it matter that we cannot?

178
00:14:05,000 --> 00:14:10,000
People once asked if maps can navigate for us, does it matter that we cannot?

179
00:14:10,000 --> 00:14:16,000
Now we ask, if machines can think for us, does it matter that we cannot?

180
00:14:16,000 --> 00:14:26,000
If machines can speak for us, grieve for us, pray for us, love for us, does it matter that we cannot?

181
00:14:26,000 --> 00:14:29,000
To me, the answer is pretty obvious.

182
00:14:29,000 --> 00:14:37,000
When I began studying human AI interaction 13 years ago, it was inconceivable to me that we would be asking these questions in my lifetime,

183
00:14:37,000 --> 00:14:40,000
but we are and we must.

184
00:14:40,000 --> 00:14:43,000
I'll leave you with this thought.

185
00:14:45,000 --> 00:14:47,000
What would you rather have?

186
00:14:47,000 --> 00:14:51,000
A tool that thinks for you or a tool that makes you think?

